social_posts.post_text: (Gets ready for bed)
Everyone at the office is an asshole. I work at home.
Haven’t shown my face in a bit. Here it is. Still looking the same.

The only two pictures that exist of my family together. Today is my mom’s birthday. She left this world many years ago. I started stand-up after she died because I was in search of something that would help me think. I’ve been working on the show I’m developing with my friend Dan and today we were sent off to script. Today on the zoom, we were all talking about how humor can be so good when it’s connected to heart and I told everyone how I closed my first special telling the true story of me telling my mom how much I loved her on her deathbed and then she didn’t die…so she kept making fun of me for telling her how much I loved her until she passed. Everyone laughed and that’s when it hit me that today was her birthday. I loved that I told that story today. She gave me the chance to live a life she could’ve never imagined possible. The picture in the top was taken outside the abandoned diner we squatted in for about 7 years. La quiero mucho mamá…como la extraño. Hay tantas veces que me imagino teniéndola aquí conmigo desciendo me, “Yo no entiendo que ven en ti pero yo que sé…” lol feliz cumpleaños, Mami. ❤️

Went to change the flowers on my mom’s grave. I haven’t been back home since before covid. She loved fake flowers. She said they lasted longer so I always get her fake flowers. Growing up, my mom would always say, “When I die, just leave me under a tree so I can get shade in the summer. It always gets so hot.” She was laid to rest next to a tree. It was not planned.

I get her a St. Jude statue because that is our family saint. She used to say that St. Jude took care of people like us, the ones that needed the most help. I don’t like to clean up her grave too much because she was from a rancho in Mexico and the dirt reminds me of it. My mom was rough around the edges and I LOVED that about her.

I cry whenever I visit her. I was thinking today about how the things that annoy you about your loved ones are the things you sometimes miss the most. My mom used to sing so loud while she cleaned the house. I used to roll my eyes at how loud. Now, I notice my brother does it and I love every single minute of it.

Hug the ones you love. You never know what random hug will stay in your mind forever. ❤️✊🏽

Visited the @foodbankrgv today. My family dealt with food insecurity a lot growing up. We never knew what a food bank was (this was before the internet). The work they’re doing here is amazing. Took a tour and learned a lot about different the different programs they offer to senior citizens, helping teachers with school supplies, a free community garden for families outside in the back to teach about sustainability and growing your own food. This work is so important. Please consider donating if you have a couple bucks. A little goes a long way, especially in the summer when kids are out of school.

I will keep on touch and see how the Food Bank and I can work together. ❤️

We couldn’t afford pay per view but we’d wait and rent the Wrestlemania VHS at Blockbuster when it came out. 

We shared a TV. My brothers had theirs. Every Monday night, I’d sit and watch WWF on USA Network. Hours. I’d sit on the floor. She sat on a patio chair we used as furniture indoors. We’d watch nonstop. We always made fun of matches that started with the unknown wrestler already in the ring while the big name got his intro. We’d joke about how we wondered who would win that one. Lol. 

I got my tomboy ways from her.

If there was a Tyson boxing match, we’d watch.

If there was an action move, especially Jackie Chan or Schwarzenegger, we’d watch ASAP.

Anyway…let’s….go….
And so it begins! #Wrestlemania39

I put this in my stories but he deserves his own post. My oldest brother Ruben. Retired schoolteacher. His old students still call him “Coach Alonzo” when they bump into him and he remembers everyone.

He worked summers in Dallas in high school to help the family. He took a loan to buy me a red Cavalier I drove to LA (that I later slept in). 

This guy doesn’t ask for anything but I would give him anything he wanted. Became a naturalized citizen in 2016 after about 30 years of trying (there is no immigration line to get into)

All I want to do now, is take him around to visit places he never thought he’d be able to for the rest of his life. The career means nothing to me if I can’t share it withy family.

I just found out that me and my stand-up is at @amhistorymuseum (National Museum of American History). I’m at a Smithsonian?

This means a lot to me. I grew up loving museums, history, art. I go to museums a lot. 😭 This little kid from San Juan, TX never imagined this could happen.  So very cool. I wish my mom was around to see this. ❤️

Thank you to @lalelilolupita for tagging me on this. I had no idea.

The man helped create worlds that left so many of us not only moved by laughter and tears…it gave some of us something to strive for.

A comedy should have serious moments. That’s life. It makes you appreciate the joy more. It has an impact that so many of us go through so many similar things, regardless of how different we may look.

RIP Norman Lear

From my first #Netflix special #LowerClassy (taped in San Antonio in 2016).

I’ve tried to be open with my struggles. I think it might make people know that they’re not alone if they’re going through something similar. I tell jokes for a living. I want to make people feel good because sometimes I don’t. My stand-up is mostly talking about my life and what I’m going through and learning. I’ll admit, I like when people can connect with what I’m saying. As different as we all may be, we are actually quite alike.

I do the work to understand the whys of it all but that doesn’t mean that it still doesn’t affect me. It’s been a long year for me, for all of us. I honestly didn’t know it was NYE tonight till someone reminded me an hour ago. 

I’m doing as ok as I can be. I am lucky enough to have the help I need and more importantly, learning to ask for the help because if you’re someone that’s been taught to do everything yourself, you don’t even think of asking.

Last time I went through a deep depression, I didn’t work for a couple of years but…this time I haven’t stopped and it’s because I’m learning to deal with it better.

I hope we can all be kinder to each other. Sometimes a kind word can go a long way to someone that needs to hear it. ❤️

I wasn’t raised in a family where we celebrated birthdays so I never do but thank you to those that wished me a good day. Every year I get to live, I am thankful for how far I’ve come.

I live in a place that has air conditioning, I do what I’ve wanted to do since I was a kid and honestly, so much more but I wouldn’t have imagined any of this when I was a little kid squatting in an abandoned diner with my family. ❤️
I never felt like I fit in anywhere but as I got older, I realized so many other people felt like that too. That’s when I realized, I belonged with them. ❤️
Just doing God’s work here by letting you know what’s up. 🧻
